76561198030080447,Recommended,269210,12109904,"Posted: 15 September, 2014",all,PrinzEugen,"Hero Siegeis likeDiablostripped to its core, with someThe Binding of Isaac-like rogue elements added as spices. It's a top-down action hack 'n slash with 16-bit graphics, to be played as one of seven distinct characters, each with their own abilities and skills. During one's walk around the arena, there's gold and (some) loot to be picked up, there are (many) monsters to be slain, and every six levels, a boss (some amazingly easy, some excruciatingly difficult) awaits you. Levels and enemies are random-generated from a relatively large numer of possibilities, which guarentees a lot of differentiation. There are - very Diablo-like.. - several chapters, each chapter having 30 (!!) levels. So far, so good: the idea is sound, the graphics are fun although a bit blurred, and the gameplay - if using an Xbox 360-like controller - is as fluid as one could hope for.ButHero Siegealso has its share of problems. The ""rpg-light""-like leveling system, with stats- and skill-points to be distributed as one levels up, is way too unbalanced. Stats go only up by fractions of percentages, making it fairly useless to upgrade them, except maybe from level 50 or so on. Action skills are sometimes VERY powerful after a time, which will be necessary - but some are really over-the-top. Opposed to this, the amount of damage one can get while playing, is completely unpredictable. This is by itself a good thing, but some bullet-firing skulls deal such an amount of damage, that during the first six levels at least, you can die in an instant without even knowing what hit you. The graphics tend to hide these skulls sometimes, and that makes it really frustrating. It's not funny to get killed out-of-the-blue without even having a hint of what hit you. Though I have to admit, once at a certain level (certainly from 31 upwards), these devils can be survived better. Power-ups, dropped by the bosses, are really essential to survive for a longer time - but since they drop randomly as well, some games are fun because of the great assets they give, others are really disappointing since you didn't get anything worthwhile for a long time.The good thing is that the developers are still finetuning things, and taking comments from the community into consideration, as far as I can see. That's why I give this game a thumbs-up, even if I've cried out sometimes in frustration when my poor newly-made marksman got out of the blue hit once more by a deadly bullet. What should really be implemented is a better save system: relics (power-ups) tend to get lost once I quit the game, and saving is actually only possible every act (30 levels).This game has potential, is strangely addictive (although the 152 (!!!) Steam achievements seem like impossible to get), but still has serious flaws. Luckily, the developers are still finetuning and working on it.UPDATE (08/15)Being curious about how the game looks and plays now, almost I year later, I started it up again, to find out some things have been improved indeed. The levelling system seems much more balanced now, there are new chapters & classes and the overall feel is more polished. However, once in-game I quickly stumbled upon the ""old problems"": some enemies/bullets can still kill you instantly, and since you can't always see them coming through the mayhem this really is bothering. Overall though, I find the game to have improved significantly over the past year.The large amount of achievements has been turned down a notch or two, so that it's easier to get a reasonable number of achievements overall.Conclusion: recommended, but not for the casual gamer looking for some easy fun"
,Not Recommended,269210,17620129,"Posted: 19 August, 2015",all,Izunundara,"Hmm, interesting alpha. Might be promising when it comes out of Early Access.It's not in Early Access?Oh.Alright.-Almost all the text in the game needs proofread. I know this isn't really much of a point because English isn't everyone's native language, but getting someone whose primary language IS English to look at the game once and say ""Yeah that's alright I guess."" is not nearly as hard as learning an entire language.-Unstable FPS. Huge FPS drops. I'm running a rig that plays most modern games at 60 FPS on max graphics.-Mouse doesn't work on some menus. For no reason.-""Beautiful sprite art"" means 5 or so average looking models for enemies which aren't even palette swapped.-Balance is an alien, nebulous concept in this game. Grinding for an hour to make your character capable of doing anything is REQUIRED.-Classes are flat and uninteresting, often with abilities that are blatantly not worth putting points in. There's an objectively optimal path for every class to skill in, so every class ends up as a copypaste. It takes an hour literally to obtain your second ability.-Character control is clunky at best. Your character feels like they are moving through glue and diarrhea.-Picking up an item does not add it to your inventory or pause the game. It vomits a comparison window over your screen, under which enemies are still murdering your♥♥♥♥♥ while you look at the vendor trash that has dropped because it still provides this nonsense for items which it highlights in red as WORSE than your current stats, yet it still asks you if you want to PERMANENTLY DISCARD YOUR CURRENT ITEM IN EXCHANGE FOR IT.-Temporary buffs that last for that life are a nice idea, except that they spiral wildly out of control after a point where you are now indestructable and kill enemies in a single shot. Losing ALL of your items on death is a kick in the♥♥♥♥♥♥ Losing ALL of your MONEY, KEYS AND ITEMS is past ""Roguelike elements"" and into Roguelite territory.-None of the stats tell you what they do. OR EVEN WHAT THEY'RE CALLED. Yes, you can figure most of it out with a little experimentation, or familiarity with the genre really. That's still not an excuse for failing to educate the player.-There are altars that upon interacting, can give you permanent upgrades to stats. Or downgrades. The first of which I found gave me nothing. The second gave nothing. The third gave me +20 Toughness (or whatever it is in this), which grotesquely overbalanced the game because the timing of which I got it made me able to instakill everything, including bosses. The next gave -40 Agility. MINUS 40. Every level up gives TWO attribute points, meaning I just lost TWENTY LEVELS' WORTH OF STATS. AT LEVEL 12. Permanently. Why not just have a background RNG that deletes your character on a 1:1000 chance every minute?-Please stop wholesale ripping off Diablo's font. It was cute the first few games, it stopped being so once we reached double figures.-NPCs in town that have ""TALK TO ME"" style blips on their head, yet have no interactions.-The Options menu has no Options. Well, that's not true, your options are ""Want at the very least resolution configuration but accept it isn't there"", or ""eat♥♥♥♥♥♥quot;.-The volume slider can be DRAGGED OFF THE SLIDER BAR. This doesn't sound like a big issue except that trying to turn the game's godforsaken audio down causes it to jump off the bar and hover over the other buttons in the menu, which take priority over it rendering it stuck at what feels like 200% volume.-Restart button gives NO CONFIRMATION, especially considering it's the exact same as dying sans the ""KILLED BY *disjointed sprite*"" screen.-Text is blurry and hard to read.-You get the ONLY TUTORIAL MESSAGE in the game EVERY TIME YOU START AN ACT. Which doesn't even cover all the controls.-It seems to have some kind of premium currency crystals which they forgot to add the Pay to Win aspect because there's not an option to buy them, yet they behave exactly like say Gems in Clash of Clans.-Entering a bonus dungeon RESETS YOUR PROGRESS ON THAT LEVEL. WHY.-Why do you explode like you die every time you go through a doorway/portal?-Crates and pots bleed.-The random map generation can sometimes, and by sometimes I mean quite regularly, spawn enemies outside the map. You have to kill them to progress. Go figure. Trying to leave the map via the gates the enemies walk in through teleports you to the spawn instead.-I SEE ITEMS BLATANTLY STOLEN FROM BINDING OF ISAAC.-One voiceover for all characters. With really crappy effects.-Ambiance effects should not run at different framerates from each other and the main entites. It looks awful.-Hitboxes for enemies seem to sometimes run on bullet hell rules where they only count as hits if it touches their source pixel.-Pirate's shots are so staggered that firing at an enemy results in every second shot passing them because the Pirate can't aim.This game feels like another one of those games that needed a sane person sitting on the chair beside the developer, overseeing the game's creation, so that they could slap the dev every time they suggested something like ""wut if we made the abilitys asplod so big dat u canit c anythin ye"". The fact that it's attempting to sell extra characters as DLC is actually repulsive. Please finish your game before you sell it. PLEASE PLEASE finish your game before you make DLC."
