,Recommended,269210,32357055,Posted: 11 June,all,Beviah,"I've been closely watching Hero Siege for quite some time, and finally made the decision to purchase it, in spite of all the negative reviews, which, I feel are entirely unjustified and should be taken with a grain of salt.Hero Siege is a hack and slash mix of Diablo III, and the Binding of Isaac.I purchased this game for a dollar and change, what I got out of it was nearly a seven hour play session with friends, I purchased the DLC, and now I'm hooked. There are some minor complaints I have with the game, which I will address, but, the good outweighs the bad.Death is not nearly as punishing as other rogue-likes, unless your character is hardcore, the game's difficulty and variables of difficulties make up for that in surplus.The Good:+ One run (DLC included) will last you around five hours, give or take, on normal difficulty with a new character.+ Each class plays very differently, making replay-ability in this game very high.+ Despite having a lot of gear, the game still provided quite a challenge.+ The game has competitive features, which allow you to test your efficiency against other players and earn special rewards, even up to rank one status.+ The combat, while can be mindless, is satisfying.+ Plenty of references to other popular games (WoW, Overwatch, Diablo, Binding of Isaac, etc.)The Bad:- There are a lot of QoL problems, for example, there is no confirmation about going through portals during acts, which can often have you leave behind items, relics, and other valuable loot, which can be frustrating.- Some items and relics are very strong, which can negate a lot of the challenge in the game. (Wings, Monkey Cloud, etc.)- The offered talent trees are very linear, which - while interesting, can be a tad dull, especially at higher levels.- There is no designated tank class at the moment, and the melee classes that are available, are at a significant disadvantage, in comparison to ranged classes.- There is no way to currently attack at an angle, only the four cardinal directions, in opposition to the standard eight in similar games.Overall, this game is charming and extremely enjoyable, it's unique. The negatives are very minor in comparison to the rest that this game has to offer and I highly recommend it to anyone. In my opinion, this game deserves a lot more positive attention and praise than what it's received thus far."
