,Not Recommended,269210,21571069,"Posted: 1 March, 2016",all,ReckedCat,"Edit - update after a year.Game is more or less the same. Balance is still an issue, visuals are still sloppy, UI is uninspired and poorly architected, but at $0.89, it'll certainly be worth your money if you play it for a few hours.That being said, my original review still stands.I can't imagine putting a hundred hours in on this game and falling back on it to really enjoy my time. There are plenty of better options out there.Honestly, wait for the game to mature. I realize it's on sale at time of posting for 90% off. Maybe pick it up and don't play for a while. The whole game seems to be fluctuating on a regular basis, and I wouldn't say I've seen the most mature responses from the development team in their update posts, or forum activity.If you want to drop a couple bucks on it and romp around a little while, have fun, and hopefully you feel the cost-benefit works out in your favor. I'll probably play some more, but I can't say I plan on investing much time or effort into speccing a character until they work out how to apply balances, and stop rubberbanding.Additional notes at time of writing:In-game button prompts and icons are only for Xbox controller. Trying to play with keyboard alone is pretty terrible, and frankly controller controls are wonky due to it being setup to play as a wasd/arrow twin-stick style shooter.Controller vibration, which is on by default, seem to occur whenever you kill an enemy, or get hit yourself. Given the bullet hell and swarm nature of the game, your controller almost never stops rumbling.Melee attack animations on enemies do not seem to line up with visual effects, leading to confusion as to why you take damage.In-game HUD for inventory is unintuitive beyond belief. Current equips on the left, with a center column that displays other equal-typed items (such as other helmets) when you're hovering over an equip slot. While hovering over an equipped item, the far right panel displays that item's detailed description. Selecting into an equip slot lets you navigate the middle pane and swap an equipped item with the item you're selecting (note, the details pane remains pointed towards the currently equipped item). Comparing the actual stats between items requires an additional button press to change the middle navigation into a detail description of the inventory item that is not equipped. Sound confusing? It's equally weird to navigate on your own.Overall, feels like a slap-dash pixel-art port of diablo, and not really in a good way.I plan to keep an eye on it for a while, but it's certainly not great."
