76561197988859028,Not Recommended,269210,13667473,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,archmando,"Binding of Isaac-like random powerups, level progression and hack'n'slash, sounds great!Too bad the basic gameplay is crazy repetitive and the feeling of progression is not there with the current skill/attribute system. Example: The Viking has a skill Stoneskin unlocked somewhere around level 18, which gives you 1% chance to ""gain a massive boost"" to armor. This massive boost is 5 points of armor, which translates into 1% damage reduction. The skill doesn't mention when does this happen, nor how long does the effect last. Most of the skills and attributes are equally underwhelming and most of the information is either hidden or wrong (Pirate lvl1 skill at rank 1 claims to do 25000 damage, lvl28 skill at rank 1 claims to do around 40, neither is even near correct).The main thing you're collecting is money, but the only place to spend it appears randomly (high chance that you'll get too much money to spend). Most of the items sold are just minor stat gains for this particular run. When your Pirate has a good chance to shoot a cannonball for 1000 damage, you really don't care about that +5 strength which would give you about 2 damage per attack.Chances are, that the game is balanced for ""end game"", but I can't seem to find the fun in trying to reach there. Was fun for a few hours, could've been way better (and apparently has been, if other reviews can be believed).TL;DR: Your generic minion available to all classes hits harder than you. If you don't care about any details how the game progression works and like hacking away, this game might still suit your needs."
