76561198044571814,Not Recommended,269210,14186226,"Posted: 26 January, 2015",all,Tahu!,"I do not reccommend this game at all, unless it goes on sale for less then $4. The so-called ""twin-stick, gauntlet style/diablo/binding of isaac/etc"" gameplay is not at all relateable, and the game turns into a hold an attack direction and wait for either an ability to go off cooldown (every 15 or so seconds) or have an ability proc an additional effect when you hit an enemy with a basic attack.When you level up in this game, you get a tiny bit of health, and a tiny bit of damage. The game jokingly gives you the option of increasing Health, Attack Speed, Defense, and Damage. You can dump every point into damage, defense or attack speed, and you will notice zero difference. What kind of damage increment is a FRACTION of one point of damage, when monsters have increasingly high scaling health in the thousands and tens of thousands within a few hours of gameplay? What is 0.01% damage protection and attack speed?? Why would they have increments so damn minor they don't even matter?? At least with the health upgrade, you can maybe survive another hit with enough points... but therein lies the next problem.This game has no difficulty curve, especially on one player. Eventually, you will be put in a situation where an attack is unnavoidable, because a projectile/enemy ability will FLASH across the screen (or off-screen) and hit you, which causes immediate death . Worse yet, enemies are capable of stunning and freezing you, even some common enemies, and they may continue to keep you locked in place permanantly until death.Virtually every boss in the game has an ability that kills you in one hit from what I've found in my three hours of gameplay. It's so horribly painful to spend so much time grinding, just to be one-shot by something you couldn't avoid. Bosses are not fun to fight....With all that being said, the reason why I -do- like this game, is because it can be fun if you are looking for some silly mindless gameplay, especially if you are the sort that likes to grind for items. Don't get me wrong, the game is still horrible through-and-through, but random luck streaks are always exciting. But the time and price investment simply do not outweigh the issuesOn a final note, multiplayer is still broken. So I guess it's permanantly single-player for a lot of folks in any case."
