,Not Recommended,269210,22695487,"Posted: 28 April, 2016",all,BabyRabbi,"The game itself is good. I just have 2 main problems with it -Nothing is explained. Nothing.There is no tutorial, no pop-up boxes, nothing. You have to figure out everything yourself. I understand that people don't like it when a game babysits the player and holds their hand, but this is the complete opposite. You create a character, and nothing is explained. You have to figure out all controls and buttons by yourself, you have to figure out how the items menu works (and the items menu is GOD AWFUL, atleast I think it's the item menu. Its just a bunch of random sized boxes and one has a chest, and if you open it its just 6 more random sized boxes appear.) The skills menu is okay, because its obvious. It tells you what skills mean and you already know what mana, health and things such as that are. You start the game by spawning into a village, and thats it. I literally went around and talked to every single person. Nobody told me anything. I got an acheivment for joining a Coffee club, though... cool?After the beginning, which confused me for 5 whole minutes trying to figure out what to do, I realized I had to walk into the Act 1 Portal all the way to the left of the town. I tried standing on the pedestal next to it for a whole minute trying to get in before realizing that the pedastals in front of it are useless and you have to walk into the actual portal. There were about 6 circles and one had an insignia on it, I thought that was me and I had to step on it. Anyway, I start the first act and enemies jump out at me on all sides. Spiders, rats, skeletons. I start holding down left click and firing, and eventually killed a lot of them. After this I got the hang of a little bit, but I still don't understand how items and specific things work. Nothing is explained to you, you have to figure all of it out on your own.My second problem with the game is this: It gets boring, very quickly. VERY quickly. Usually in a game such as this, there are ways to keep the player excited and interested during waves and battles. For example, Orcs must Die or Dungeon Defenders add towers, and you want to keep fighting to keep getting better towers. Something like that, just something special to seperate the game from just running around and fighting...thats basically what this game is. The game (or Atleast Act 1 as I played it) Is literally just running around in circles in a very small, boring map while holding down left click and occasionally going to my stats to click some buttons after I level up. I assume the game gets fun when its more fast paced, but it starts off so slowly, I don't understand how somebody could have fun trying to get into this game. I greatly enjoy games of this genre (Hack N' Slash enemies coming in waves), and I will play this game farther to see if it gets more interesting or helps me out, but so far, the game has a tedious and boring start and the rest of the game doesn't look very promising. I got this game on sale for .99 cents late last year, so if you really want to see if this game is alright, pick up during the summer sale or something, maybe you'll get your money's worth.Oh yeah, I should probably say this too, you get a few classes when you start. About 6-7. The rest (about another 5-6) are locked behind a paywall. Not just .99 cents per class, nope. Each comes with a DLC pack. So if you want all the classes, you have to buy all the DLC, and all the DLC together is about 30$. There is quite a bit of content locked behind a paywall. So if your okay with paying 6$ for the game and 29.92$ for the missing chunk of content, be my guess. This game is like looking at the Mona Lisa (We'll say this represents the video game genre) and asking if you could have another painting like that for a cheap price. You pay 6$ and get a nice painting of a man, but its colored with such vivid strangeness you can't tell what your looking at until you look it up. After you look at the painting a bit, you realize that the top right corner of the mans face is missing in the painting, and you have a giant hole in the middle. You ask for the middle and they charge you 30$ For it.That sounds stupid, but that's basically what this game is. A decent game with a fair chunk of it locked behind a greedy scheme to take more money out of you, and such a poor presentation that it can be hard to get into, especially if you're knew to this genre. If you want to play a good game in this genre, try Orcs Must Die (2), Dungeon Defenders, or just play Zombies on Call of Duty. I hate Call of Duty, but I would probably enjoy playing Naz' Zombies with my friends doing 4 player couch co-op then being restricted to only 2 players with no introduction or assistance to the player.Edit: Something I forgot to mention, I hope the whole game isn't like this, but Act 1 is very...dark. The screen is very dark black and you have a small ring of light around you. That kind of thing just doesn't seem right with me, I feel like having a dark room and you can't see anything but the enemy's health bar just doesn't work for this type of game."
