,Not Recommended,269210,11542188,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Takalol,"PS: Pardon if you are the devs and are spending time trying to balance out and make this game better, just ignore my review and go on with your lives, work hard and make it a good game so I can recommend it. I will correct this review if the game makes up for my expectations in the future.PPS: This review will present some terms adherent to MMORPGs, other games, or just terms that I created since I am lazy to look out for the correct terms to be used. I am going to start this review by poiting out the good sides of this game and why someone would buy it. Then pointing out my opinions (which are mostly negative) on this game based on other similar games I've played, or games with similar mechanics that are pretty referenced within this game.First of all, this game looks very promising, it has many mechanics that may work in the future if more polished, it has many things that would work if the developers spent more time on it  has a pretty good presentation and a good amount of references hidden within, the Character creation looks like Diablo 2, the skill builds work similarly to Diablo 2 too, both mechanically and aesthetically, the way the light goes through the stage after finishing it looks a lot like the Den of Evil from the same game, the game makes lots of references of The Binding of Isaac too, which is another roguelike that has many similar mechanics. I would point both of them as being the main drivers of this game, along with Diablo 3, that has many mechanics ""referenced"", such as the elite enemies, some of them have similar powers, such as Cold Enchanted freezing the player character for some seconds that may kill him, while others may explode and send out a globe of laser that (will, most of the time, if unseen) kill the player character too. I like the way the developers tried to create many classes and how they try to work differently, the necromancer summons minions to aid him, while the Viking goes straight for melee combat doing hard crowd control. The game is separated in acts, just like the now-so-famous Action RPGs, it also resembles old time games such as Smash TV, you wait for the monsters to come, and exterminate them while trying to dodge them and stuff like that. Okay, end of the positive parts.If the developers were trying to make their game similar to The Binding of Isaac + Blizzard Stuff + Pixel Art + Original IdeasGold feels useless for most of the time, while crystals are just ""cash"" that can be used on some pretty cute/cool stuff like hats, it is also used for resetting the character or renaming it, these character features should be free or with small work needed by default to incentive players to change names and try new different builds, but are pretty expensive.Damage done by the player is extremely hard to see, numbers are small and travel too fast, and are also decimal.Hidden traps can be utterly strong without previous knowledge since the player couldn't see them, and are mostly luck based when they spawn, if it hits the player, the mobs or nothing. Grabbing potions on the ground may mean player's death if she happens to grab one that is among the gold/loot while a blood maggot/other strong mob is shooting at you. Since the players stops all animations for extremely valuable 0.5 sec.Some bosses will 1 shot a squishier character with no way to read how much damage they would deal, just like the ""girl spirits""  Annie or Samar, they just spawn going lightning speed toward the player while dealing like 50% damage in 1 hit, no clue what happened and just died. Also, their projectiles don't look like dealing THAT much damage.Voice acting is terrible, wish there was a way to shut it down completely, because there is no way.Now for the main part:The Game feels totally incomplete and unpolished, at times I thought it was a Early Access and had to go to the Store Page to check if it really wasn't. Most of the Controller based commands feel incomplete, e.g.: ""B"" is used to call a new wave, while ""B"" is also used to close the level up menu, if you press B to close the level up menu while you are able to call a wave, it'll do both.Trees and most of the props are just hindering player's vision too much, just too polluted, I know that the intention was to hinder the player, but since the player can't tell what is behind 100% of the trees, sometimes there is a ultra-strong 1 hit killing turret/statue trap and the player can't tell it, just killing the player by full surprise.Most of the ""spheres"" that monsters throw to the sky when dying are broken, blue, red, yellow, they are always off screen unless the player is north of the monster that throws it.Sometimes monsters have ""0"" HP on their bars but still alive, some monsters get stuck on their own paths and cannot reach me going forwards and backwards non-stop, somesome bosses are ridiculously easy, like Beketamun, while others need extremely high skill from the player to be able to kill him, like ones that laser around non-stop, bosses like that need a open-area for the player to be able to move, but they walk after the player and sometimes it just means death if summoned on the wrong place. Such as near a Statue Trap.dungeons are like rolling a d20 to see if you get out alive or not, some dungeons may present you with a screenful of godlike enemies on the instant you enter it, the area that the player has to deal with bosses inside dungeons is also pretty small, there is nigh-none space to fight bosses, and there are also bosses that are summoned that are ultra-strong for particularly enclosed spaces. There are also other dungeons that may be empty with a free treasure for the player with just some small puzzle before it. Entering dungeons is just too high of a risk for lower leveled characters, since the chances of dying because of a unlucky boss or unlucky room are very high. While it may present free relics for higher leveled characters, it just stacks with the grind needed to become ""successful"".So far most of my deaths have been to the Blue Sphere on-kill effect from monsters, I've played plenty of Diablo 3 to know where this mechanic came from, so, In Diablo 3, sometimes monsters had the ""Arcane Enchanted"" property, which happens to be a similar mechanic, when they die, they leave a purple sphere on the place of their death, which exists for 1 second before firing a ""laser needle"" which spins and deals huge damage, the main problem with Hero Siege's ""Arcane Enchanted"" is that it is only a sphere that's thrown out of screen at the monster's death, when it comes back it is already firing the laser, seeing the shadow of the ball is pretty difficult considering the amount of trees, grass, monsters and shots on the screen, most of the time it is instant death for the player if it happens to fall on his head, that is if no traps spawn on the player's feet insta killing.- It seems to me that the Devs didn't play their own game before releasing 1.0, or if they did and enjoyed it, they must have a pretty taste for artificial difficulty. Some bosses can kill you while on their death animations, due to the lightning globes that keep spawning when the player damages them while they are dying.most sprites are far from being user friendly, since it's hard to tell what's ""friendly particle"" to a ""foe particle"".- There is no catalogue to check the item list, I know that the Twin Blades give me Critical Chance, but how much Crit%? I can't even see my critical chance on the menu in first place. If this is intentional, it feels pretty odd when playing.There is almost no room for faults since most of the stuff will 1-hit the player, I know that the developers must've made it their way, but when playing on hardcore it is just too unforgiving.tl;dr: dont buy it, too luck/grind based instead of skill, unpolished, broken mechanics sluggishly borrowed from other games. My tip, go for Risk of Rain for roguelike, Path of Exile for action"
