76561198070367189,Not Recommended,269210,13072588,"Posted: 24 November, 2014",all,T0k1n0va,"Hero Siege is a twin stick shooter inspired by diablo, so you get things like healing wells, dangerous magic on death etc.the levels are set up as arena hold out stages where you are supposed to fend off waves of enemies.Here's the short version. There's a real review bellow.ProsCool level design.Cool Character design.minidungeons.Cons.bad hitboxes.VERY grindy.slow progression.boring items.boring abilities.You level up and get 2 stat points and one ability point. there are 4 stats to choose from; strength, attack speed, armor, health, and putting one point into any of the first three stats will increase it by a fraction. this is fairly useless when enemies have health values in the hundreds, and attack values high enough to be unaffected by a 0.40 increase in your armor. The ability point is really the only thing you will care about when you level up. you can spend the point in a branching ability tree. the first tier of the tree has two options, an active, and a passive, the passives increase chances, or whatever the ability is supposed to affect, by 1 measely percent, so the obvious choice is to choose the active ability, which is pretty interesting to be fair. the downside is that this active ability is all you're going to get until you are level five. this makes the game progress very very slowly.one of the stranger things about the game considering its inspirations, is that there are very few items to collect. loot comes along once in a great while, and your first item is likely to be uninteresting. upon beating the first boss an item spawned on a pedestal in front of the portal, it was a green double crescent blade and ot gave me a SLIGHT increase to  my crit chance. the boss itself dropped a token for me that gave me a stat tradeoff attack +4 armor -2. both of these were terribly dissapointing. I killed a drake type boss, and as such i expected an item to reflect that, perhaps an item that had to do with shooting a fireball or having enemies burn the ground on death, but all i got was a change to my numbers.probably the hardest part of the game to swallow was the awful hitbox detection. i spent a long time getting used to simply hitting enemies. everything is a 2d sprite in sort of an isometric view, which makes it inherently more difficult to judge differences between distances. This can be a nightmare when fighting spiders, which have a large sprite, but a tiny hitbox. and certain classes are particularly bad at hitting enemies, in this case namely the pirate has a hard time because her pistol shots alternate between her left and right hand, which occupy different planes which makes it more than likely you will miss half of your shots unless you're very very used to her. Melee characters are also terrible because their attack animations extend beyond their hitboxes. Compare this with the binding of isaac, it has the same 2d models and the same view, but its fairly clear where you're firing and all that good stuff.In conclusion, play either diablo or play binding of isaac. This game wants to be both, but it doesn't do either very well. If you see the game on sale, go ahead and buy it, just know that it isnt a tight and clean experience."
