,Not Recommended,269210,13465709,"Posted: 19 December, 2014",all,Fargin Noob,"What we have here is a fairly decent start to a roguelike that quickly gets consumed by its own weaknesses. You start every game at the beginning: great. You can upgrade your character through progression: super. Your upgrades stay with you when you restart: just what I wanted.After that though, we encounter the two biggest design flaws for the game. First, the ratio of player power to enemy power doesn't follow appropriately and you soon find yourself in a situation where the enemies are far too powerful. Second, the fact that you can only fire in four directions means you are severely limited in what you can hit at any given time; plus, enemies have no such restriction, making the design choice questionable at best. The combination of these two things means there is a definite ""correct build"" that you must go through to get very far into the game, which for this type of game reduces player agency in their progression.The graphics are very well done, with high-quality pixel art and a great palette. There's never any confusion because of graphics as to what's going on, with the slight exception that it can be difficult to see your character or other enemies when they're behind something, like a tree, even with the fade out of the object. Not sure what the fix is to this, but it's only just ""okay"" as it is.The sound feels powerful and the music is good, but not terribly memorable. All in all, the game starts off letting you feel like you're doing very well but quickly descends into an exercise in futility. After a point, you never really feel very powerful any more and you just see the progression as a chore. That's unfortunate because there's a lot of potential here.All in all I don't think I can recommend the game, not because it isn't fun for a while, but more because it should be fun for a lot longer and isn't. The difficulty curve doesn't track in a way that pushes you to keep coming back, but instead punishes you for doing well early on, punishes you for minor mistakes, punishes you for not being able to see behind objects, and punishes you if you've made the wrong build along the way.If there were a ""maybe"" button, I'd select that. Since I can't, I'd say skip this and go for any number of other games like it that are better."
