76561198046047877,Not Recommended,269210,14327970,"Posted: 4 February, 2015",all,Thrakmor,"When I first bought this game I enjoyed it, I really did. But that quickly wore off as it was more of an excitement from trying something new than actual fun. The game is NOT a bad game, but that does not mean it is a good game. I currently feel like the game has a lot of potential, but is underdeveloped, underplanned, and at some points just completely half-a**ed.There are a good ammount of characters to choose from, each with their own set of active and passive abilities. But besides that they can all be grouped into one of two categories: Melee and Ranged. Melee characters get close to the enemies and swing at them, Ranged characters stay farther away and shoot. The only real variation are the abilities, which most of the actually useful ones are passives that usually have a 1% chance of activating per point put into the skill, or are actives that do not scale in damage per point as well as they should and sometimes make the character a ""press x to win"" type of character. Besides the abilities characters get seperate attribute points that can be used to make the character have more health, do more damage, attack faster, or take less damage. Like the abilities, these scale very poorly per point spent, requiring many points to actually have a decent effect.Besides the abilities relics are found in the game, usually by defeating the level boss, and also affect the game somehow. Some of the relics are passives that affect either the character or the enemies. Others are active abilities that are used and then are put on cooldown for a short ammount of time. Some of the relics are extremely powerful and borderline OP. Most of the relics, including the powerful ones, are really not that important and often inspire feelings of ""oh, that relic."" instead of ""YES! I got this relic!""Combat is pretty basic. Characters can attack either left, right, up, or down. Combat mostly consists of the character being close enough to hit the enemies, and backing up so that they are not hit themselves (also known as kiting). The only real threats are enemies with ranged attacks, or certain enemies with special abilities. From my experience the most variation in combat has been activating a relic, potion, or active ability, or a passive ability activating. The potion system is pretty standard for some rogue-likes and rogue-lites. If a potion is picked up for the first time, the effects of that potion is unknown until it has been drunk. Afterwards the effect has been learned and other potions of that color will display the effect. Note: The effects of the potions change from run to run. Once a character dies, whether hardcore or not, the effects of all potions are changed.Multiplayer: I have not tried multiplayer, as I have felt no desire to. The game is not good enough to keep me wanting to play as it is currently, and joining a server with strangers is very unlikely to make me want to play the game more.All in all, this game feels too simplified, like someone took a great game, and stripped away anything ""complicated"" only the bare bones of the game were left. This game is good for people looking for a simple casual game, but it is not for people looking for a good diablo-style game."
