,Recommended,269210,9231474,"Posted: 23 February, 2014",all,Bastion,"This is a really nice game.Is it worth full price? I would say yes.Your goal is to beat the waves that come at you by using your attack. There are different classes, and the attack is different for each one. There is only 1 attack per class, but each class has abililities and perks that can modify the class specific attack, which is very nice indeed. For instance, as a pyro, the base attack is a ball of fire, but as you level up you can improve the chance of instead of firing a ball of fire, you fire a meteor, or even fire the base ball of fire in multiple directions. There's all sort of crazy things you can do really.As you beat waves, you go trough different areas. Those areas are different each time you play (they are somewhat randomly generated), and different areas have different traps and enemies. What i mean by ""somewhat randomly generated"" is that for instance the size of the area, the type of the enemies, and the type of traps you can expect in one area it's always the same, but they are placed in different locations each time, and some instances may or may not have some traps. That makes each play-trough unique, and you may have to adopt slightly different strategies each time.Killing enemies gives you experience, which you use to level up. When you level up you are given points that you can spend on improving your stats. There are 4 stats in the game, those being Damage, Attack Speed, Armor and Health. Also, you receive points to improve/unlock abilities or the chances of your base attack do something different. It's also a rogue-like, in the sense that if you die on one wave, you're done and you have to start from the Wave 1 of the act all over again. Though, unless you're playing on Hardcore, you keep you character, its levels, points, abilities etc.. Part of the point of the game is level up so you're stronger the next time you play.The game also features dungeons, that appear on the areas of the game. The dungeons sometimes are harder to beat than the normal waves, but they give you an item if you beat the dungeon, so it's more often than not worth the risk. Those special items, called ""relics"" are also given to you each time you beat an area, and they really improve you experience with the game. Those items do all sort of crazy things. Some give you base attack a chance of freezing/poison enemies, others give you homing missiles that are around you that fire automatically and help you killing the enemies, others ""simply"" improve your base stats etc... I say ""simply"" because even though ""improve you base stats"" may sound something boring, it can REALLY help you out making areas easier. These items are also wiped from you if you die, so you have to collect new items again each time you play. The game seems to have a finite number of these relics, but there's a large number of them and the items you find are also randomly generated.As you kill enemies they drop gold, that you can spend on the store on thing like health potions, damage boost potions etc. Those boosts are also only valid for that specific play-trough, they reset if you die, as well as all the gold you happen to find. The game has also a rare currency, the crystals. These crystals are really hard to find, as far as i know there's only 2 ways to get them: crystal chests (chests that need a crystal key to be opened) or bosses that sometimes drop a few of them, very rare to happen though. With crystals you can buy cosmetic stuff, the possibility of have a skeleton pet the next time you play (that actually helps you fight the enemies), the possibility of starting with a relic on your next playtrough, crystal keys. You might be like ""Hang on a minute..you say you can get crystals from crystal chests, but you have to spend crystals on crystal keys to open them, what?"" Yes, the good news is that those crystals chests often give you more crystals than the ones you spent on the key, along side with tons of gold and possibly a relic. And for those wondering, i'm happy to say that the game has no microtransactions whatsoever.I really recommend this game. Already put 10hrs on it and will definitively put more.The only word of warning advice before buying this game it's that even though it's on sale as a completed game, it is not. As the time i'm writing this, new classes and multiplayer are promised and are still to be added. Some balance improvements are still being made. It's more like a beta, but with a pretty solid gameplay already."
