76561198099436742,Recommended,269210,21696258,"Posted: 7 March, 2016",all,WRTH Rysek,"I played this game for only around 5 hours, and I'm already in love with it. I just finished Act I with 4 legendary pieces of armor, and Hero Seige has only gotten more fun over the time. There are a couple down sides to it however, but we'll get into that after I state the pros. So, let's get into the details.The game is quite addicting. While it can get a bit repettitive if you're, quite frankly, bad at it, since you face the same monsters and bosses every time you play, if you're skilled at the game you can pass Acts ""quickly"". Each act has it's own bosses, monsters, traps, etc. The one things that I have found to stay the same is the drops and the layouts of the dungeons and crypts. Even after I beat Act I and got into the snowy act, the crypts and dungeons are still the same textiles as before, dirty. This may be for a reason, since it is underground, but I would have liked to seen some more details, perhaps at least some snow, or maybe some other factor that would indicate the low temperature. One thing I liked about changing acts is that it seems that the previous act's bosses are the new act's normal enemies. For example, a boss called ""Annie"" that appeared on the first act, appeared as a normal enemy with her health in the next act. Another thing I like about Hero Siege is it's replayability. While it may get a little boring once you beaten all the acts with each character, and I highly doubt many people have done it, each time you play a new act, or a new character, the fun factor doesn't decrease. Hero Siege brings a lot of new content to the table for each of it's components. Each acts has different bosses, enemies, traps. Each character has different weapons, abilities, and special buffs. For example, my Demon Slayer has a lot of health and speed, while my friends Samurai seemed to have a lot of attack damage and got a lot omore experience then me. Which brings me to another point, this game can be played single player, and be extremely fun. While this may seem like a wierd point, and it is, since I can't really word it correctly, I have to give an example. Basically, I can sit down at my PC, skype a friend, and we can both play in our own single player worlds, talking to each other about new things we would, and new bosses we're fighting, and our stats, weapons, relics, etc. Almost none of the games I've ever found had that feature where I can just talk to someone about thsi game and have a lot of fun. So, I may have left a lot out of the game in terms of pros, and I have, I need to be starting on the cons.One of the main problems I have about this game is it's terrible multiplayer support. Normally on Steam games, you can just press join game or something of that nature. In Hero Siege, you have to make your own server by port-forwarding, which not a lot of people know how to. But that's not an issue for me, other than that I can't port-forward, as in it just doesn't work on my computer. My problem is the amount of bugs in multiplayer. I have seen some update logs, and I can see that they are fixing a lot of them, so I guess that good. Another con with this game is how the learning isn't exactly steep, but just ""there"". People who are bad at the game can't exactly get better. The good loot is with the hard to defeat enemies, and without that, you can't really get better. You're just... stuck? Another thing that I didn't like was that the bosses difficulty fluctiuated, alot. Sometimes I would face a boss that I could one hit on round 24, and then I would face a boss that would one hit me on round 6. They definitely need to change the boss strength to make each boss equal to each other. Another thing that bothers me is that the bosses never really get harder. I'm not talking about through acts, but through the rounds, one boss is as easy as another. When I played the first time, the first boss was extremely hard, and I found pleasure in that. Over the time, as I got better and better loot, I found that none of the bosses leveled up to match my skill. I could instantly take them down, and sometimes, I wouldn't even notice they were bosses. That's due to some of the bosses and almost all of the mini-bosses being re-colors of other enemies. I would like the bosses and the enemies get higher in stats as I level up, since now it's just kind of boring to go through the earlier rounds. I just skip them all, and then just shoot them down easily. Other than that though, the game has really no more disadvantages that I can think of.So, now the real question, would I recommend this game? Yes, definitely. I am recommending this to all my friends at school, and even some out of school. If you're not really good at games like this, more so, terrible at games like this, don't get it. You won't really advance and it'll just be boring. However, if you can handle a challenge, and be patient with the game to level up and get your equipment, I promise this game will be a good buy, I only noticed this game when it was on sale for $.050, and I got the 4-pack. I would probably have gotten it even for it's $6 price now."
