76561197990571227,Not Recommended,269210,13682596,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,Tankeater,"While Hero Siege can provide fun for a few hours, it is not a game with much replay value and I only found myself sick of it after a few hours.  While I didn't max out any characters or make it to the later acts, I was able to complete act 1 without much difficulty and played a good deal of act 2.  The game itself is a hack 'n' slash (which I respect), but it has so many balance issues there is only one way to approach gameplay.  You can't create a brash tank, a wily theif, a sinister necromancer, or a restoring cleric.  All you can create are glass cannons.Gameplay involves circlestrafing enemies in an arena for hours on end and hoping not to get 1shot by something you literally cannot see.  Projectiles are 1000x more lethal than melee attacks, and the amount of♥♥♥♥♥♥on screen after act 1 means that in order to survive you are relying more on luck than any actual skill.  Unfortunately, the pacing for act 1 is so slow that you spend more time hunting down stray enemies than you do anything else.  Do not make the mistake of trying to conquor a random dungeon, as they are usually a suicide mission.  Enemies will randomly spawn on you, or you will get stuck fighting off a horde of enemies in a diagional hallway when you can only attack NSEW.  Most bosses in the game are laughably easy, being much slower than you and often having no projectile attacks.  Other bosses will spawn and start casting a spell.  The boss will just say ♥♥♥♥ the channel time and instantly 1shot you with a cross-screen NSEW laser attack that pierces all terrain.  I'm pretty sure he just waits for you to get NSEW of him then he lets loose with an instagib.I created several characters, and even when putting EVERY stat point into HP and defense you will still get 1shot or 2shot by any enemy in the game.  It makes stat points feel irrelevent when the stat distribution does nothing to affect gameplay.  Your skill build is pretty relevant, but some skills and passives are totally useless or bonkers overpowered.  Some low cooldown aoe skills have +500 damage per skillpoint, while some single target abilities have +40 damge per skillpoint.  At least a respec is cheap.  Trying to grind for a level advantage is pretty impossible.  Luckily for me, a type of elete enemy spawns waves of weak flies, and killing a small swarm of these will net you 1-3 levels in experience.  Fly swarms have probably given me 60-75% of my total character xp.Items are pretty underwhelming in most cases, and give you a paltry amount of +stats.  Picking up charms and potions is a deathwish in many situations.  Trying to pickup a charm pops up an equipment comparison window, but while you compare stats, you find yourself getting brutalized by terrain hazards.  Potions on the other hand cause you to pause in place and hold them over your head (item get!), while enemies swoop in for free killing blows on your character.  When you are actively running away from enemies, it's really obnoxious to have a minefield of potions littering the battlefield, and many of them are totally obscured behind houses, trees, and particle effects.This isn't the worst game I've ever played, and I may try playing again sometime, but it has serious issues that make it hard to enjoy.  I feel like I've given it a decent chance, and while the game has its merits, I will make a point of doing more research on games I buy in the future becuase I don't like my steam library cluttered up with games I don't enjoy.6/10 would buy again for $3"
